<HEAD>Treaty Questions Raised by Planned Anti-Missile Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics say a planned Star Wars test in the
South Pacific comes close to violating a 1972 treaty outlawing
major missile defenses.
   Near the middle of the month, a Boeing 767 equipped with a 3-ton
infrared sensor will make its first attempt to track a mock warhead
on an intercontinental ballistic missile fired from Vandenberg Air
Force Base, Calif.
   The plane is scheduled to depart Boeing Field in Seattle on
Monday for a two-day trip to Kwajalein Atoll, an Army missile test
range in the Pacific.
   Anti-ballistic missile radar is prohibited by the 1972 ABM
Treaty between the United States and the Soviet Union.
   John Pike, head of space policy at the Federation of American
Scientists and a Star Wars critic, said the aircraft ``appears to
be the functional equivalent of an ABM radar.''
   Pike said the Soviets may be justified in questioning whether
the airborne sensor is a treaty violation.
   ``If we saw the Russians doing this kind of thing, we would be
pretty bent out of shape about it, and if the Russians were giving
the explanation we are, we wouldn't believe them,'' Pike said.
   The Army says the airborne sensor is not a prototype for an
anti-missile sensor system. It also argues that the aircraft could
not substitute for an ABM radar because of technical limitations in
its infrared sensor and its on-board computers.
</TEXT>
